comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Georg Friedrich Brandes (1709-1791) was a German jurist, overseer(?) of the University of Göttingen, and collector of books and art. The bulk of his notable library, some 22000 volumes, was sold in 1790 to Peter Friedrich Ludwig, Duke of Oldenburg (1755-1829) and formed the basis of the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg (founded 1792 and still in existence). This is unlikely to be the "Brandes sale" in question. Brandes also collected engravings, however, and Michel Huber published a 2-volume catalog of the collection under the title Catalogue raisonné du cabinet d'estampes de feu Monsieur Brandes, secrétaire intime de la Chancellerie royale d'Hannovre (Leipzig: Rost, 1792-1794). These engravings appear to have been sold at auction in 1796. Two separate sales were planned: the first at Easter (18 April), comprising the English, German and Italian items; the second at Michaelmas (3 October), comprising items from France and the Netherlands. Cf. "Verkauf des Brandes'schen Kupferstich-Kabinets" in Neue Bibliothek der schönen Wissenschaften und der freyen Künste 56 (1795): 189-190, as well as the two sale catalogues: Premiere partie ou Écoles angloise, allemande et italienne, avec une grande collection de portraits: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de Pâques 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1795) and Seconde partie ou Écoles des Pays-Bas et Francoise: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de S. Michel 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1796). The book in which this ms. note is written should contain 3 engraved plates (a portrait of the author, Willibald Pirckheimer, by Albrecht Dürer; Pirckheimer's arms by Heinrich Ulrich; and an allegory of Tribulatio, Spes, Tolerantia and Invidia after a sketch by Dürer), but all are wanting. For more information on Brandes's library, including reproductions of his bookplate, see the online exhibition at the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg here, as well as G. Crusius, Aufklärung und Bibliophilie: Der Hannoveraner Sammler Georg Friedrich Brandes und seine Bibliothek (Heidelberg: Winter, 2008). Crusius also deals briefly with the engravings collection. Established form: Brandes, Georg Friedrich, ǂd 1709-1791.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Illustrated armorial bookplate of Christian Ernst, Graf zu Stolberg-Wernigerode (1691-1771). According to E.A. Washburn, "Ex-Libris in a Medical Library", Bulletin of the Medical Library Association 27.4 (1939), p. 233, "Ernst's private library of 115,000 volumes, containing many medical books, was open to the public." Harvard University, in an online note describing its Stolberg Collection, elaborates:
The golden age of the Stolberg library was during the reign of Christian Ernst (b. 1710-1771). He not only greatly increased its holdings and opened it to the public, but was also its librarian, commissioning the distinctive Stolberg bookplate and personally inscribing the publication date on the spine of each volume bound in white vellum. In 1746 Christian Ernst issued an edict making the collection—by then about 10,000 volumes—a public library.
The book in which this plate appears is indeed bound in pale vellum parchment and has the imprint dates of its contents in ms. on the spine. Established form: Stolberg, Christian Ernst, ǂc Prinz, ǂd 1691-1771.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Definitely from the 1551 edition by Aquila of this work; cf. the reproduction in P. Simoniti, "The 1551 Herbenstein-Wernher Description of Lake Cerknica," Acta Carsologica 39.1 (2010), p. 150. Simoniti also contends that it is "highly likely that the motif for the woodcut of Lake Cerknica had been drawn by the famous Nürnberg painter, graphic artist and cartographer, Augustin Hirschvogel (1503-1553)" (p. 157). Penn's copy of De admirandis Hungariae aquis hypomnemation (1551), bought as part of the same transaction as this work (Chorographia Transylvaniae), wants the plate. Rudolf Hirsch conjectures that both of these works were disbound from a Sammelband owned by Sigismund von Herberstein, the dedicatee of De admirandis Hungariae aquis hypomnemation (cf. "Georg Wernher and Sigismund von Herberstein," Gutenberg Jahrbuch (1963), p. 121). Established form: Hirschvogel, Augustin, ‡d 1503-1553. Established form: Aquila, Aegidius, ‡d 1496-1552. Established form: Herberstein, Sigmund, ǂc Freiherr von, ǂd 1486-1566.

comment.text:
Woodcut printer's device of Govaert Bac of Antwerp. Cf. Bac's entry in M. Harman, Printer's and Publisher's Devices in Incunabula in the University of Illinois Library (Urbana, Ill., 1983):
The "bird cage" in this device is Bac's housemark, his address being "int vogelhuys." It is the device of his predecessor at this shop, Matthias van der Goes. Bac changed the initial, M, of Van der Goes, to his own initials, g b, and added his own mark, the good-luck symbol, 4, double-crossed and surmounted by a swastika. The shield bears the arms of the city of Antwerp, the two severed hands issuing from the central tower allegedly being derived from the practice of punishing pirates by cutting off their hands and throwing them into the Schelle. This is the third of several versions of this device, which was first used in 1496.
Established form: Bac, Govaert.

comment.text: Bookplate, identified in pencil ms. (not visible in image) as that of "William Jackson [of] Paris" (fl. 1865-1880?). According to M. McGatch, Jackson was "a pastor who resided in Paris and whose library was dispersed by the firm of Otto Harrassowitz, Leipzig, in 1910," adding in a footnote, "Jackson's nationality is unknown. George Lincoln Burr refers to him as 'the Paris pastor' with a 'rich Reformation collection'" (The Library of Leander Van Ess (New York: Bibliographical Society of America, 2007), p. 29). Harrassowitz's auction catalog describes this collection as "die Bibliothek des verstorbenen französischen Sammlers William Jackson in Paris, die etwa um die Mitte der sechziger Jahre des vorigen Jahrhunderts begonnen und von dem Sammler bis etwa 1880 mit ebenso intensivem Eifer wie feinsinnigem Verständnis ausgebaut wurde" (Bibliotheca theologica William Jackson (Leipzig: Harrassowitz, 1910), p. [iii]).* *Translation: the library of the deceased French collector William Jackson in Paris, which was begun about the middle of the sixties of the last century and developed until 1880 by the collector with as much intense zeal as sensitive understanding.

comment.text: Iesus saluator filius perducat nos superius vbi regnat in gloria Raynutius In Nomine Sancte et Indiuidue trinitatie [sic?] patris et filij et spiritussancti Amen Nouerint vniuersi [The first line comes from the hymn "Ave fuit prima salus". "Raynutius" may be a name (> "Rinucci"?) or refer to a chapter of canon law known by the name of one of the litigants in the case that gave rise to it. The sketch of three horses appearing above the trinitarian formula of the signum crucis might possibly refer to the passage in St. Augustine's work De Trinitate (book 7, chapter 3) where he uses three horses as an example in discussing the meaning of the word "person" as it refers to the Christian God. Or they could just be a sketch of three horses, but I find the coincidence interesting.]

comment.author: 58558794@N07
comment.text:
From the bookseller's description laid into the volume:
Apparently the only edition.  An extremely rare Blado imprint, not listed by Fumagalli & Belli and not in the British Museum.  It is a privately printed book, circulated among the princes of the Holy Roman Empire by the Prince Bishop of Hildesheim, Valentin von Teutleben (reigned 1537-1551). Dated September 24, 1538, it is directed against the Dukes Eric I of Brunswick-Lueneburg and Henry the Younger of Brunswick-Wolfenbuettel who in the famous struggle known as Hildesheimer Stiftsfehde (1519-1523) had invaded the Hildesheim territory with the help of the King of Denmark. In the peace treaty, signed in 1523, John, Duke of Saxe-Lauenburg, bishop of Hildesheim, had surrendered nearly all his possessions. In the present work, Teutleben, his successor, contests the annexation of his land, which, however, was only recovered during the Thirty Years' War.
Schottenloher, <u>Bibliogr. z. deutschen Geschichte im Zeitalter der Glaubensspaltung, Vol. III, No. 29766 A.</u>

Biblioteca Magnani, a large collection of about 25,000 volumes, was bequeathed in 1811, to the Biblioteca comunale in Bologna, by Antonio Magnani (1743-1811), professor and librarian of the Institute of Sciences (Istituto delle Scienze). In 1817, Biblioteca Magnani was incorporated into the Biblioteca comunale and for a while the library was called Biblioteca comunale e Magnani, in recognition of the importance of the Magnani fund. In 1838, the library moved to the Palazzo dell’Archiginnasio and was enriched with collections from the suppressed religious orders.

Nowadays, Biblioteca comunale dell'Archiginnasio still holds a Magnani special fund ("Fondo speciale Antonio Magnani"), which includes his personal papers and a significant number of manuscripts and valuable editions of books.

comment.text: Gold-stamped armorial device with initials "W.H. B. v. G". Description: a pot (or a bowl) with three legs in a shield surrounded by leaves; the pot repeated on the helmet between two feathers. This matches the description of the arms of the Grappendorf family in Germany. One of the most preeminent members of this family was Baron Wilhelm Hilmer Von Grappendorp, Freiherr [baron of] von Rueustadt, Grapenstein, etc. who married Luise Amalia Wilhemine von Billich in 1727. I think he is the former owner of this book; his initials match the ones on our book (B is most probably coming from baron)

comment.author: 58880069@N07
comment.text: He is not established and the only dates I could find for him were 1726 and 1727 (when he got married). So, I guess he will be Wilhelm Hilmer von Grappendorp, baron.

comment.text: There seems to be a lot of variation in the spelling of the last name. I find Grapendorff, Grappendorff, Gropendorf, Grapendorf,Grappendorp, etc. Also I sometimes see Hilmar in addition to Hilmer. The most frequent combination is Hilmar von Grapendorff. I found one Wilhelm Hilmar Freiherr von Grapendorf listed as an Oberjägermeister in Prussia. The dates are blurry in the text, but it looks like he was Oberjägermeister from 1764-1782.
